## Detailed Implementation Plan: Extract Business Logic into a Service Layer

### 1. Overview and Approach

The goal is to move all business logic out of Express route handlers into pure service functions. The route handlers will become thin adapters that (a) parse HTTP input, (b) call a service function, and (c) translate the service result into an HTTP response.

**Error handling strategy: Custom error classes with a `statusCode` property.** This is the recommended approach over result objects for this codebase because:
- The existing code already uses early-return patterns with different HTTP status codes and error messages -- thrown errors map naturally to this pattern.
- Result objects would require every caller to check `if (!result.success)` at every call site, adding boilerplate without adding clarity in a codebase this size.
- Custom error classes allow a single `try/catch` in each route handler (or even a shared error-handling middleware), keeping the handlers maximally thin.
- TypeScript's `instanceof` checks give type narrowing on the error, so the route handler can extract `statusCode` and `message` cleanly.

---

### 2. New Files to Create

**`src/services/errors.ts`** -- shared custom error class
**`src/services/productService.ts`** -- all product business logic
**`src/services/orderService.ts`** -- all order business logic

No other new files are needed.

---

### 3. `src/services/errors.ts` -- Custom Error Class

A single error class is sufficient. Every service function that encounters a user-facing error throws a `ServiceError` with the appropriate HTTP status code and message. The route handler catches it and forwards both to `res.status(...).json(...)`.

```typescript
export class ServiceError extends Error {
  public readonly statusCode: number;

  constructor(statusCode: number, message: string) {
    super(message);
    this.name = "ServiceError";
    this.statusCode = statusCode;
  }
}
```

**Why a single class instead of separate NotFoundError, ValidationError, etc.?** Because this codebase has exactly two status codes in play (400 and 404). Separate subclasses would add indirection without adding value. The `statusCode` property carries the same information. If the project grows and needs richer error semantics later, subclasses can be introduced then -- but for now this keeps it pragmatic.

